T1  - The Pragmatics of “Really Mattering” on Policy Issues: William Ouchi as Exemplar
AU  - Weick, Karl E.
Y1  - 2005/12/01
PY  - 2005
DA  - 2005/12/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amj.2005.19573104
DO  - 10.5465/amj.2005.19573104
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 986
EP  - 988
VL  - 48
IS  - 6
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - The article discusses the contribution management scholar William Ouchi has made towards making management more relevant to policy issues. Ouchi has spent 35 years studying large business organizations, with a particular emphasis on how controls affect autonomy and outcomes within an organization. While studying a large public school system he determined that a key source of dysfunction was individual schools' lack of autonomy. When school principals are held accountable while having more scope for decision-making, Ouchi showed, the result was a more responsive system.
AB  - The article discusses the contribution management scholar William Ouchi has made towards making management more relevant to policy issues. Ouchi has spent 35 years studying large business organizations, with a particular emphasis on how controls affect autonomy and outcomes within an organization. While studying a large public school system he determined that a key source of dysfunction was individual schools' lack of autonomy. When school principals are held accountable while having more scope for decision-making, Ouchi showed, the result was a more responsive system.
